Keep in mind that type guards are not foolproof, and they can only narrow the type of a value based on the conditions that you specify. If the conditions are not exhaustive, the type system may still infer a broader type than what you intend. Therefore, it's important to use type guards judiciously and only when you're confident that they accurately reflect the runtime behavior of your code.

